<font color="#FF0000">QUESTIONS &amp; ANSWERS</font><br>
<tt>Sun Dec  1  9:58:00 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
Mr. Winkler - I can't speak for Mr. Riddle, I'm sure he's quite capable of doing that for himself.  I can tell you that I didn't serve &quot;without question&quot; - hell I got more questions than you can believe.  However, I did not know the answers to many of those questions until I saw it with my own eyes.  As I stated in my original letter, the people who got us into 'Nam weren't thinking &quot;Hey, let's kill tens of thousands of Americans and millions of Vietnamese just for the hell of it&quot;, they were responding to what they felt were genuine threats.  Your historical analysis is &quot;correct&quot; - the Cold War did shape their vision and led them to do terrible things.  The only thing your historical analysis lacks is humanity.  What would YOU have done, given their same experience and background?  I think very few people could have done much better.<br><br>
What would I have done if I'd been at My Lai?  I sure hope I wouldn't have pulled the trigger.  Would I have tried to save some of those folks?  I don't know that I would've had the courage.  And guess what?, there were thousands of little My Lai's every day we humped the boonies.  Why's that kid looking at me that way?  Why did that woman change direction so quickly when she saw me?  Why did that old man cross the bridge by my post 3 times in the last hour?  Questions, questions questions...all day every day.  Should I put my foot HERE or should I put my foot THERE?  Answer the question wrong and you lose your leg, your nuts your life - maybe your buddy's life too.  Like I said, I got tons of questions.  Problem is, I'm a little short on answers.<br><br>
If the Vietnam War can teach us anything, it can teach us that NONE of us has all the answers, not even you.
<p><code>-- miketol@mtco.com  (Mike Toliver) </code><p>


